<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910425-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>910425-0038.</DOCID><HL>   New York City's '92 Deficit   May Widen to $3.6 Billion</HL><DATE>04/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><NS>ECONOMIC NEWS, TRENDS, INDEXES, PROJECTIONS, ANALYSES (ECO)</NS><RE>NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- New York City's fiscal 1992 budget deficitcould widen to nearly $3.6 billion if tax revenues continueto decline, City Comptroller Elizabeth Holtzman said.   The latest estimate is $389 million higher than the $3.2billion budget gap that the city comptroller's officeestimated two months ago. The recalculation was based on thecity's tax collection and employment data for March, Ms.Holtzman said.</LP><TEXT>   The current forecast lowers the city's fiscal 1992personal income tax revenue estimate by $182 million, salestax revenue by $173 million, property tax revenue by $25million and other business taxes by $9 million.</TEXT></DOC>